# Rust Development Guidelines

Directives for Rust development. Apply when working with `.rs` files or `Cargo.toml`.

---

## Ownership and Borrowing

- Prefer borrowing over moving when the caller needs the value afterwards; use `&T` or `&mut T`.
- Move by default when transferring ownership; assignment moves for non-`Copy` types.
- Clone only when necessary ‚Äî cloning is explicit and can be expensive; prefer references.
- Use `&str` over `&String` for function parameters when you only need to read.
- Return owned values from functions when the caller should own the result; avoid returning references to local data.
- Borrow mutably (`&mut T`) only when you need to modify; avoid overlapping mutable borrows.
- Use `into_iter()` when consuming a collection; use `iter()` when you need references.
- Do not return references to temporary or stack-allocated data.

```rust
let s1 = String::from("hello");
let s2 = s1;   // move; s1 invalid
let s3 = &s2;  // borrow; s2 still valid
```

---

## Lifetimes

- Add explicit lifetimes when the compiler cannot infer them (e.g. function returns a reference derived from parameters).
- Rely on elision when the rules apply: one input ref ‚Üí output ref gets that lifetime; one `&self`/`&mut self` ‚Üí output ref gets that lifetime.
- Use `'static` only for data that lives for the whole program; avoid for general-purpose APIs.
- Structs holding references need lifetime parameters: `struct Excerpt<'a> { part: &'a str }`.
- Prefer owned types when lifetimes make the API complex; sometimes `String` is simpler than `&str` in public APIs.

---

## Smart Pointers

- **Box\<T\>** ‚Äî Single ownership, heap allocation; use for recursive types, large values, or trait objects.
- **Rc\<T\>** ‚Äî Shared ownership, single-threaded; use when multiple owners need the same value (e.g. graphs, shared config).
- **Arc\<T\>** ‚Äî Thread-safe shared ownership; use when sharing across threads; pair with `Mutex` or `RwLock` for mutability.
- Avoid Rc/Arc when possible ‚Äî they add overhead; prefer borrowing or owned values when ownership is clear.

---

## Error Handling

- Use `Result<T, E>` for fallible operations; use `Option<T>` for optional values without an error.
- Propagate errors with `?` instead of manual `match`; keep `main` and library boundaries in mind for error types.
- Use `thiserror` for library error types: derive `Error`, implement `Display`, use `#[from]` for wrapping.
- Use `anyhow` for application code when you need flexible error handling and context.
- Avoid `unwrap()` and `expect()` in production ‚Äî use `?`, `match`, or `if let`; reserve `expect()` for invariants with a clear message.
- Prefer `unwrap_or_else` over `unwrap_or` when the default is expensive to compute.

---

## Performance

- Use iterators ‚Äî they are zero-cost abstractions; prefer `iter().map().filter().collect()` over manual loops.
- Prefer `&[T]` and `&str` over `&Vec<T>` and `&String` for function parameters.
- Use `Vec::with_capacity(n)` when the final length is known to avoid reallocations.
- Use `Cow<'a, T>` when you may return either borrowed or owned data to avoid unnecessary cloning.
- Avoid allocations in hot paths ‚Äî reuse buffers, use `String::clear()` and `Vec::clear()` instead of creating new ones.
- Prefer `iter()` over `into_iter()` when you only need to read; use `into_iter()` when consuming.

---

## Concurrency

- Prefer channels (mpsc) for message passing between threads; they avoid shared mutable state.
- Use `Arc<Mutex<T>>` when multiple threads need shared mutable access to the same data.
- Use `Arc<RwLock<T>>` when reads dominate writes; `RwLock` allows multiple readers or one writer.
- Use `thread::spawn` for CPU-bound work; use async for I/O-bound work.
- Join spawned threads ‚Äî call `join()` to handle panics and ensure completion; avoid detached threads unless intentional.
- Move data into threads with `move`; clone `Arc` when sharing across threads.

---

## Async

- Use `tokio` for async runtimes in applications; use `async`/`await` for I/O-bound operations.
- Use `tokio::spawn` for concurrent tasks; use `join!` or `futures::join_all` for awaiting multiple futures.
- Avoid blocking in async code ‚Äî use `tokio::task::spawn_blocking` for CPU-bound or blocking work.
- Prefer `#[tokio::main]` for application entry points; configure the runtime (e.g. `multi_thread`) as needed.
- Use `?` in async functions ‚Äî they work with `Result`; ensure error types implement `From` for propagation.

---

## Testing

- Unit tests ‚Äî place in `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` in the same file; use `#[test]` and `use super::*`.
- Integration tests ‚Äî place in `tests/*.rs`; each file is a separate crate; test public API only.
- Arrange‚ÄìAct‚ÄìAssert ‚Äî set up data, perform the action, assert the outcome.
- Use descriptive test names ‚Äî e.g. `test_returns_error_when_email_invalid`; avoid generic names.
- Test error paths ‚Äî use `assert!(result.is_err())` or `#[should_panic]` where appropriate.
- Use `cargo test` ‚Äî run tests; use `--no-fail-fast` to see all failures.

---

## Cargo Configuration

- Release profile ‚Äî use `opt-level = 3`, `lto = true`, `codegen-units = 1`, `panic = "abort"` for smaller, faster binaries.
- Feature flags ‚Äî use `[features]` and `#[cfg(feature = "name")]` for optional functionality; avoid default features that pull in heavy deps.
- Dev-dependencies ‚Äî put test/bench-only crates (e.g. `criterion`, `proptest`) in `[dev-dependencies]`.
- Edition ‚Äî use `edition = "2021"` for new projects.

---

## Common Anti-patterns

- Unnecessary cloning ‚Äî prefer `&T` or `&mut T`; clone only when ownership is required.
- `unwrap()` in production ‚Äî use `?` or explicit handling; `expect()` only for documented invariants.
- Overly complex lifetimes ‚Äî consider owned types or restructuring to simplify.
- `Rc<RefCell<T>>` without justification ‚Äî often a design smell; prefer clearer ownership or `Arc<Mutex<T>>` for threads.
- Blocking in async ‚Äî avoid `std::thread::sleep` or blocking I/O in async functions.
- Ignoring compiler warnings ‚Äî fix or document; do not suppress without reason.
- `Box<dyn Error>` everywhere ‚Äî use `thiserror`/`anyhow` for structured errors in libraries and apps.

---

## Checklist

- [ ] Borrow when possible; clone only when necessary
- [ ] Use `Result`/`Option` and `?`; avoid `unwrap()` in production paths
- [ ] Prefer iterators over manual loops for collections
- [ ] Use `Vec::with_capacity` when size is known
- [ ] Channels for message passing; `Arc` + `Mutex`/`RwLock` for shared state
- [ ] Unit tests in `#[cfg(test)]`; integration tests in `tests/`
- [ ] Release profile tuned (LTO, `codegen-units = 1`, `panic = "abort"`)
- [ ] Feature flags for optional behaviour; minimal default features
- [ ] Australian English in comments and user-facing strings
